						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Value-chains-Innovate-to-include-the-poor" title="Value chains: Innovate to include the poor" alt="link">Value chains: Innovate to include the poor</a></h2>

	
					<p>Refocusing on the poor turns many value chain principles on their head, believes William D. Dar, ICRISAT’s DG, writing on his blog about the difference between Inclusive Market-Oriented Development (IMOD) and the conventional value chain approach. Conventional value chains tend to favour the participation of larger-scale, wealthier farmers for easier management and quality control. Transforming value chains to include the poor requires ‘systems innovation’ – innovation that enables large numbers of people to participate while still remaining manageable and meeting market demands for consistent product quality and volume. To illustrate his thoughts, Dar goes into the details of goat marketing project underway in Mozambique that created a goat auction system with benefited both the abattoir and the smallholder goat sellers.<a href="http://witblog.icrisat.org/?p=1208" target="_self">http://witblog.icrisat.org/?p=1208</a>ILRI <a href="http://clippings.ilri.org/2013/03/25/small-stock-connections-lead-to-better-business-for-goat-keepers-in-zimbabwe" target="_self">comments</a> on the project.Market-oriented development innovations in the smallholder goat value chain in southwestern Zimbabwe<a href="http://paepard.blogspot.nl/2013/03/market-oriented-development-innovations.html" target="_self">http://paepard.blogspot.nl/2013/03/market-oriented-development-innovations.html</a>(ICRISAT, 03/2013)</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/05/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Value-chains-Innovate-to-include-the-poor">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/ICGEB-to-strengthen-and-expand-biosafety-systems-in-sub-Saharan-Africa" title="ICGEB to strengthen and expand biosafety systems in sub-Saharan Africa" alt="link">ICGEB to strengthen and expand biosafety systems in sub-Saharan Africa</a></h2>

	
					<p>The International Centre for Genetic Engineering and Biotechnology (ICGEB) has received a grant exceeding US $6 million from the Gates Foundation for the implementation of a project to assist the regulation of agricultural biotechnology products in sub-Saharan Africa. The project will be carried out by the Centre’s Biosafety Unit, by personnel based in its Trieste (Italy) and Cape Town (South Africa) components, and will focus on the development of effective safety and regulatory systems for the regulation of genetically modified organisms.<a href="http://www.icgeb.org/news_English/items/icgeb-receives-grant-from-gates-foundation.html" target="_self">http://www.icgeb.org/news_English/items/icgeb-receives-grant-from-gates-foundation.html</a>(ICGEB, 11/2012)</p>
							<p><span class="date">22/05/2013</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/ICGEB-to-strengthen-and-expand-biosafety-systems-in-sub-Saharan-Africa">Read more...</a>
